## 🎨 UI/Frontend Development Standards

### Responsive Design (Mobile-First)
- **Mobile-first approach**: Base styles for mobile, scale up with media queries
- **Use relative units**:
  - `rem` for font sizes (1rem = 16px browser default, respects user settings)
  - `em` for component-relative spacing
  - `%` or viewport units (vw, vh) for container widths
  - Avoid `px` except for borders, shadows, or pixel-perfect requirements
- **Fluid typography**: Use `font-size: clamp(1rem, 2vw + 1rem, 2rem)`
- **Fluid layouts**: Use CSS Flexbox and Grid (avoid fixed widths)
- **Standard breakpoints** (use `em` in media queries for accessibility):
  - Mobile: < 40em (640px) - base styles, no media query
  - Tablet: 40em - 64em (640px - 1024px)
  - Desktop: 64em - 90em (1024px - 1440px)
  - Large: > 90em (1440px+)
- **Media query pattern**: `@media (min-width: 40em)` not `max-width`
- **Touch targets**: Minimum 44x44px (Apple) or 48x48px (Google)
- **Minimum spacing**: 8px between interactive elements
- **Responsive images**: Use `<img srcset="...">` or `<picture>` element with multiple sizes
- **Image optimization**: Lazy loading (`loading="lazy"`), modern formats (WebP with fallback)
- **Proper aspect ratios**: Use CSS `aspect-ratio` property
- **Typography standards**:
  - Line length: 45-75 characters for readability
  - Line height: 1.5-1.6 for body text, 1.2-1.3 for headings
  - Typography scale: use modular scale (1.25, 1.333, 1.5, or 1.618 ratio)
- **Hover states**: Enhancement only (not required for functionality)
- **Use `@media (hover: hover)`**: For hover-specific styles
- **Support both touch and mouse**: Interactions must work for both
- **Respect system preferences**: 
  - `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`
  - `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)`

### Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 Level AA Compliance)
- **Semantic HTML**: Use `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<article>`, `<section>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>`
- **Proper heading hierarchy**: `<h1>` to `<h6>` in order (no skipping levels)
- **Button vs link**: Use `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation (never swap them)
- **Form labels**: Every form input must have associated `<label>` (explicit or implicit)
- **Tables**: Use `<table>` only for tabular data with proper `<th>`, `<caption>`, `<thead>`, `<tbody>`
- **ARIA labels**: Use when native semantics insufficient (`aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, `aria-describedby`)
- **ARIA roles**: For clarity (`role="navigation"`, `role="banner"`, `role="search"`, `role="complementary"`)
- **ARIA states**: For dynamic content (`aria-expanded`, `aria-hidden`, `aria-current`, `aria-disabled`, `aria-selected`)
- **Live regions**: For dynamic updates (`aria-live="polite"` or `"assertive"`, `aria-atomic="true"`)
- **Don't override native HTML**: Don't override native HTML semantics with ARIA unless necessary
- **Keyboard navigation**: All interactive elements accessible via Tab, Enter, Space
- **Visible focus indicators**: `:focus` and `:focus-visible` styles (outline minimum 2px)
- **Logical tab order**: Follows visual reading order
- **Modal/dialog focus management**: Trap focus inside, Escape to close, return focus on close
- **Skip navigation links**: "Skip to main content" at page top
- **Alt text**: Descriptive for meaningful images, empty (`alt=""`) for decorative images
- **Descriptive link text**: Avoid "click here", "read more" without context
- **Form error messages**: Associated with inputs via `aria-describedby` or inline
- **Loading indicators**: Announced to screen readers with `aria-live` or `role="status"`
- **Color contrast**: 4.5:1 for normal text (<18px), 3:1 for large text (18px+ or 14px+ bold)
- **Don't rely on color alone**: Use icons, text, patterns to convey information
- **Support high contrast mode**: Test with high contrast enabled
- **Test with screen readers**: NVDA (Windows), JAWS (Windows), VoiceOver (Mac/iOS), TalkBack (Android)
- **RTL support**: If needed, use logical properties (`margin-inline-start` not `margin-left`)
- **Set language**: `<html lang="en">` or appropriate locale
- **Avoid flashing content**: Content that flashes more than 3 times per second (seizure risk)
- **Captions/transcripts**: Provide for audio/video content

### Performance Optimization
- **Critical CSS**: Inline in `<head>` (above-the-fold styles)
- **Non-critical CSS**: Load asynchronously or deferred
- **JavaScript**: Defer (`<script defer>`) or async loaded
- **Code splitting**: Load only necessary code for current page
- **Lazy loading**: Images (`loading="lazy"`), iframes, below-the-fold content
- **Preload critical resources**: `<link rel="preload" href="..." as="style|script|font">`
- **Prefetch likely next pages**: `<link rel="prefetch" href="...">`
- **DNS prefetch**: For external domains `<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="...">`
- **Minification**: HTML, CSS, JavaScript (remove whitespace, comments)
- **Compression**: Gzip or Brotli for text-based resources
- **Bundle size budget**: Enforce maximum sizes (e.g., <200KB gzipped initial load)
- **Tree shaking**: Remove unused code from bundles
- **Image optimization**: Proper compression, next-gen formats (WebP, AVIF)
- **Responsive images**: Serve appropriate size for viewport
- **SVG for icons**: Use SVG for icons and simple graphics (smaller than raster)
- **Icon fonts or SVG sprites**: For multiple icons
- **CDN for static assets**: Images, fonts, libraries
- **Minimize DOM size**: Avoid deeply nested structures (>1500 nodes slow)
- **Batch DOM manipulations**: Read all, then write all (avoid layout thrashing)
- **Use `requestAnimationFrame`**: For animations (60fps target)
- **Debounce scroll/resize/input**: Handlers (300ms typical)
- **Throttle frequent events**: Mousemove, scroll for parallax
- **Virtual scrolling**: For long lists (>100 items)
- **Web Workers**: For heavy computations (keep main thread responsive)
- **Service Worker**: For offline support and caching strategy
- **HTTP caching headers**: Cache-Control, ETag
- **LocalStorage/SessionStorage**: For client-side data (5-10MB limit)
- **IndexedDB**: For larger client-side datasets
- **Core Web Vitals targets**:
  - Largest Contentful Paint (LCP): < 2.5 seconds
  - First Input Delay (FID): < 100 milliseconds
  - Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS): < 0.1
- **Additional metrics**:
  - First Contentful Paint (FCP): < 1.8 seconds
  - Time to Interactive (TTI): < 3.5 seconds
  - Total Blocking Time (TBT): < 200 milliseconds
- **Avoid layout shifts**: Set width/height on images, reserve space for dynamic content
- **Font loading**: `font-display: swap` to prevent invisible text (FOIT)
- **Subset fonts**: Only include required characters/weights
- **Self-host fonts**: When possible (faster than Google Fonts often)
- **Reduce third-party scripts**: Each adds latency and security risk
- **Analyze bundle composition**: Regularly (webpack-bundle-analyzer or similar)

### Cross-Browser Compatibility
- **Target browsers**: Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge (last 2 major versions minimum)
- **Mobile browsers**: Safari iOS, Chrome Android, Samsung Internet
- **Progressive enhancement**: Basic functionality works everywhere, enhancements for capable browsers
- **Feature detection**: Check for capability before using (not browser detection)
- **Vendor prefixes**: Use Autoprefixer or PostCSS plugin (don't manually prefix)
- **Fallbacks for modern features**: CSS Grid with Flexbox fallback
- **CSS feature queries**: `@supports (display: grid) { ... }`
- **JavaScript feature detection**: Before use
- **Polyfills**: For missing features (only when needed, after feature detection)
- **Transpile modern JavaScript**: ES6+ for older browsers
- **Check caniuse.com**: For feature support before using
- **Test in all target browsers**: Real devices preferred over emulators
- **Avoid experimental features**: Without fallbacks
- **Handle differences**: Safari date input, IE11 Flexbox bugs (if supporting)

### User Experience (UX) Patterns
- **Loading states**: Spinners, skeleton screens, progress bars
- **Loading indicator**: For operations >300ms
- **Skeleton screens**: For content-heavy pages (better than spinners)
- **Progress bars**: For multi-step processes
- **Success feedback**: Toast notifications, inline confirmations, banners
- **Error messages**: Clear, actionable, specific (not generic "error occurred")
- **Position errors**: Near the problem (form field errors next to field)
- **Form validation**: Real-time feedback on blur or after first submit attempt
- **Validation timing**: Validate on blur, show success on input correction
- **Required fields**: Clearly marked with asterisk and `required` attribute
- **Disabled states**: Visually distinct (lower opacity), explain why disabled if not obvious
- **Empty states**: Helpful message with next action ("No items yet. Add your first item!")
- **Smooth animations**: 200-300ms duration for micro-interactions
- **Animation easing**: Ease-out for entering, ease-in for exiting
- **Transition specific properties**: Not `all` (performance)
- **Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`**: Remove/reduce animations
- **Hover effects**: Subtle, don't overwhelm (color change, underline, slight scale)
- **Click/tap feedback**: Visual change on active state (ripple, scale, color)
- **Drag and drop**: Clear drop zones, visual feedback during drag
- **Breadcrumbs**: For deep navigation hierarchies
- **Active page/section**: Highlighted in navigation (with `aria-current="page"`)
- **Mobile navigation**: Hamburger menu, bottom tab bar, or full-screen overlay
- **Back button**: Must work correctly (don't break browser history)
- **Avoid scroll hijacking**: Or unexpected scroll behavior
- **Smooth scrolling**: For anchor links (`scroll-behavior: smooth` or JavaScript)
- **Page transitions**: Subtle, fast (<300ms)
- **Pull-to-refresh**: On mobile (if applicable - native-like apps)
- **Infinite scroll**: Include pagination fallback for accessibility
- **Search autocomplete**: Debounce input, show loading, handle empty results
- **Tooltips**: Appear on hover (desktop) and tap (mobile), dismiss on Escape or outside click
- **Modals/dialogs**: Close on Escape, close on backdrop click, prevent body scroll
- **Forms**: Autofocus first field cautiously (accessibility concern)
- **Input masking**: For formatted data (phone, date, credit card)
- **Autocomplete attributes**: For common fields (name, email, address, etc.)
- **Show/hide password toggle**: For password inputs
- **Character count**: For limited inputs (e.g., "140/280 characters")
- **Inline validation**: With debounce (check availability, validate format)
- **Success state**: After form submission (don't just redirect silently)
- **Graceful degradation**: When features fail (show error, offer retry)
- **Retry mechanisms**: For failed requests (exponential backoff)
- **Offline mode messaging**: Clear indication when network unavailable
- **404 pages**: Helpful, with navigation back to main content
- **Network error handling**: User-friendly messages (not technical jargon)
- **Confirmation dialogs**: For destructive actions (delete, leave unsaved form)
- **Undo option**: For reversible destructive actions (alternative to confirmation)

### CSS Architecture & Best Practices
- **Organization structure**: base → layout → components → utilities
- **Base**: Resets, typography, global styles
- **Layout**: Grid systems, containers, spacing
- **Components**: Reusable UI components
- **Utilities**: Single-purpose helper classes
- **Naming convention**: BEM (Block Element Modifier) or consistent alternative
- **Example**: `.card`, `.card__title`, `.card--featured`
- **Avoid `!important`**: Design system should prevent need
- **CSS custom properties**: For theming (`--color-primary`, `--spacing-unit`)
- **Logical properties**: For RTL support (`margin-inline-start` instead of `margin-left`)
- **Modern CSS layout**: CSS Grid for two-dimensional, Flexbox for one-dimensional
- **Container queries**: For component-level responsiveness (when broadly supported)
- **CSS nesting**: When broadly supported (keeps related styles together)
- **Subgrid**: For aligned nested grids (when supported)
- **`aspect-ratio` property**: For maintaining proportions (with fallback)
- **`gap` property**: For spacing in flex and grid (cleaner than margins)
- **Avoid float-based layouts**: Use Flexbox/Grid instead
- **Avoid absolute positioning**: For layout (use for overlays, dropdowns only)
- **Class-based styling**: Preferred over ID-based (IDs too specific)
- **Scoped styles**: When possible (CSS Modules, Shadow DOM, or namespacing)
- **Consistent spacing scale**: 4px or 8px base unit (e.g., 0.25rem, 0.5rem, 1rem, 1.5rem, 2rem)
- **Consistent color system**: Primary, secondary, accent, semantic (success, warning, error, info)
- **Consistent typography scale**: Modular scale for predictable sizes
- **Consistent shadow scale**: Subtle to prominent (3 levels typically sufficient)
- **Consistent border radius scale**: None, small, medium, large, full
- **Motion design system**: Consistent timing functions and durations
- **Icon system**: Consistent size, style, and implementation method
- **Z-index scale**: Define layers (e.g., base, dropdown, overlay, modal, toast)

### Component Design Principles
- **Single Responsibility**: Each component does one thing well
- **Reusability**: Design for multiple contexts, not single use case
- **Composability**: Components combine to create complex UIs
- **Atomic design**: Atoms (buttons) → molecules (search bar) → organisms (header) → templates → pages
- **Props/attributes API**: Flexible but opinionated (good defaults, allow overrides)
- **Composition over configuration**: Prefer slots/children over massive prop lists
- **Avoid prop drilling**: Use appropriate state management for deep hierarchies
- **Component size**: Keep under 250-300 lines (split if larger)
- **Extract complex logic**: Separate presentation from behavior
- **Meaningful names**: Component purpose clear from name
- **Internal state**: For UI concerns only (toggle dropdown, animation state)
- **External state**: For data and business logic
- **Style encapsulation**: Component styles don't leak globally
- **Theme support**: Use CSS custom properties or design tokens
- **Documentation**: Describe props, usage examples, edge cases
- **Variants system**: Size (sm, md, lg), color (primary, secondary), state (default, hover, active, disabled)
- **Accessibility baked in**: Components accessible by default

### Security (Frontend)
- **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Restrict script sources, prevent inline scripts
- **XSS prevention**: Sanitize user input, escape output, use framework's built-in escaping
- **Never use `innerHTML`**: With user input (use `textContent` or framework's safe rendering)
- **Avoid `eval()`**: `Function()` constructor, `setTimeout/setInterval` with strings
- **CSRF tokens**: For state-changing operations (forms, API calls)
- **Secure cookies**: HttpOnly (no JavaScript access), Secure (HTTPS only), SameSite=Strict/Lax
- **Don't store sensitive data**: In localStorage/sessionStorage (not encrypted, XSS vulnerable)
- **Use httpOnly cookies**: For authentication tokens
- **Input validation**: Client-side for UX, server-side for security (never trust client)
- **Rate limiting**: Prevent brute force, DDoS (implement server-side)
- **Sanitize file uploads**: Validate type, size, scan for malware (server-side)
- **Avoid inline event handlers**: Use addEventListener (better CSP compliance)
- **Subresource Integrity (SRI)**: Verify third-party scripts haven't been tampered
- **HTTPS everywhere**: No mixed content (HTTP resources on HTTPS page)
- **Redirect HTTP to HTTPS**: Always
- **Don't log sensitive data**: To console in production
- **Redact sensitive info**: In error reporting services (Sentry, etc.)
- **Cookie consent**: For GDPR/CCPA compliance
- **Session timeout**: For sensitive applications
- **Logout functionality**: Clear all session data
- **Clickjacking prevention**: X-Frame-Options or CSP frame-ancestors
- **Open redirect prevention**: Validate URLs before redirecting

### Testing Requirements
- **Unit tests**: Individual components in isolation (70% of tests)
- **Integration tests**: Component interactions and API calls (20% of tests)
- **End-to-end tests**: Critical user flows, happy paths (10% of tests)
- **Visual regression tests**: Catch unintended UI changes (screenshots comparison)
- **Accessibility testing**: Automated checks with axe-core, pa11y, or Lighthouse
- **Manual accessibility testing**: Keyboard navigation, screen reader testing
- **Performance testing**: Lighthouse CI in deployment pipeline
- **Cross-browser testing**: Automated (Selenium, Playwright) or manual
- **Mobile testing**: Real devices preferred over emulators
- **Test user interactions**: Not implementation details
- **Test edge cases**: Empty states, error states, loading states, long content
- **Test responsive behavior**: Different viewport sizes
- **Minimum 70% code coverage**: For UI components
- **Mock external dependencies**: API calls, timers, random values
- **Snapshot tests**: For complex UI (use sparingly, brittle)
- **Test naming**: Describe behavior, not implementation ("shows error when input invalid")

### Code Quality & Standards
- **Linting**: ESLint (JavaScript), Stylelint (CSS), HTMLHint (HTML)
- **Formatting**: Prettier for consistent code style
- **Pre-commit hooks**: Lint and format before commit (Husky, lint-staged)
- **EditorConfig**: Consistent editor settings across team
- **Type safety**: TypeScript, JSDoc type annotations, or PropTypes
- **Meaningful names**: Components, functions, variables explain purpose
- **Small functions**: Single responsibility, <50 lines preferred
- **Avoid magic numbers/strings**: Use named constants
- **Comment complex logic**: Explain "why" not "what"
- **Self-documenting code**: Clarity over cleverness
- **Consistent indentation**: 2 or 4 spaces (team decision)
- **Consistent quotes**: Single or double (team decision)
- **Trailing commas**: Yes (easier diffs) or no (team decision)
- **Semicolons**: Yes or no (team decision, enforce with linter)
- **Remove dead code**: Commented-out code, unused functions/variables
- **Avoid deeply nested conditionals**: Early returns, guard clauses
- **Avoid long parameter lists**: Use options object for >3 parameters
- **DRY principle**: Extract repeated code into functions/components
- **KISS principle**: Simple solutions over complex ones
- **Avoid premature optimization**: Profile before optimizing
- **Component library documentation**: Storybook, Styleguidist, or similar
- **README**: Setup instructions, development workflow
- **Changelog**: Document breaking changes and new features

### Internationalization (I18N) & Localization (L10N)
- **Externalize all user-facing text**: No hardcoded strings in code
- **Translation keys**: Descriptive, namespaced by feature
- **Pluralization support**: Different text for 0, 1, many
- **Number formatting**: Locale-based (1,000.00 vs 1.000,00)
- **Date/time formatting**: Locale-based (MM/DD/YYYY vs DD/MM/YYYY)
- **Currency formatting**: Locale-based ($1,000.00 vs 1.000,00 €)
- **RTL language support**: Arabic, Hebrew (use logical CSS properties)
- **Text expansion**: Reserve 30% extra space for translations (German often longer)
- **Avoid text in images**: Use HTML/CSS text for translatability
- **Language switcher**: Accessible, preserves user state
- **Default language detection**: Browser settings or geolocation
- **Fallback language**: When translation missing

### Deployment & Monitoring
- **Environment configurations**: Development, staging, production
- **Environment variables**: API URLs, feature flags, credentials
- **Optimized production builds**: Minification, compression, tree shaking
- **Source maps**: Generate for debugging, store securely (not public)
- **CI/CD pipeline**: Automated build, test, deploy on merge
- **Preview deployments**: Automatic for pull requests
- **Error tracking**: Sentry, Rollbar, Bugsnag (capture client-side errors)
- **Analytics**: User behavior tracking (Google Analytics, Mixpanel, Amplitude)
- **Real User Monitoring (RUM)**: Performance metrics from real users
- **Session recording**: Hotjar, FullStory (privacy-aware, GDPR compliant)
- **A/B testing**: Feature flags for gradual rollouts (LaunchDarkly, Optimizely)
- **Performance monitoring**: Track Core Web Vitals, set up alerts
- **Uptime monitoring**: Ping checks, alert on downtime
- **CDN**: Use for global asset delivery (CloudFlare, Cloudinary, Fastly)
- **Cache invalidation**: Strategy for updating cached assets (cache busting)
- **Rollback capability**: Quick revert if deployment issues

### Progressive Web App (PWA) Considerations
- **Web App Manifest**: Name, icons, theme color, display mode
- **Service Worker**: Offline support, caching strategy
- **Installability**: "Add to Home Screen" functionality
- **App-like experience**: Full screen, no browser chrome
- **Push notifications**: With user permission, not intrusive
- **Background sync**: Queue actions when offline, sync when online
- **Offline fallback page**: Show when no cached content available
- **Update strategy**: Notify user of new version, prompt to refresh

### Form Best Practices
- **Label every input**: Visible label or `aria-label`
- **Placeholder is not a label**: Use proper `<label>` element
- **Input types**: Use specific types (email, tel, url, number, date) for better mobile keyboards
- **Autocomplete attributes**: Help browsers autofill (name, email, tel, address, etc.)
- **Required fields**: `required` attribute and visual indicator (asterisk)
- **Optional fields**: Mark as "(optional)" if most fields required
- **Field grouping**: `<fieldset>` and `<legend>` for related inputs
- **Error messaging**: Specific, actionable ("Email must contain @" not "Invalid input")
- **Error placement**: Inline near field, or summary at top of form
- **Error styling**: Color + icon (don't rely on color alone)
- **Success indication**: After validation passes (green checkmark, success message)
- **Disable submit button**: During submission (prevent double submission)
- **Submission feedback**: Loading indicator, disable form, success message
- **Preserve input on error**: Don't clear valid fields when validation fails
- **Multi-step forms**: Progress indicator, back button, save draft
- **Large forms**: Autosave or warn before leaving page (unsaved changes)
- **Password requirements**: Show upfront (not after failed validation)
- **Password strength indicator**: Visual feedback as user types
- **Confirm password field**: Only for high-stakes scenarios (often unnecessary)
- **Show/hide password toggle**: Eye icon, accessible label
- **Input masking**: Phone numbers, credit cards, dates (format as user types)
- **Character/word count**: For limited inputs (Twitter-style)
- **Field validation timing**: On blur or after first submit attempt (not on every keystroke)
- **Success validation**: Immediate feedback when correction made

